<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk, Clinton Discuss Wide Range of Issues </TI></H3>
<H4>   Spokesman: Time for `Expanded' Dialogue </H4>
<F P=102> WS1201154594 Kiev Ukrayinske Radio First Program Network in 
Ukrainian 1505 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> WS1201154594 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev Ukrayinske Radio First Program Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] During the meeting between Ukrainian President 
Kravchuk and U.S. President Bill Clinton, a wide range of issues 
concerning bilateral Ukrainian-U.S. relations will be discussed. 
This was stated by Viktor Stelmakh, head of the Ukrainian 
Council of Ministers' and presidential press service on 12 
January in an interview with the NOVYNY Television and Radio 
Agency. He pointed out: It is not difficult to predict that 
both issues of bilateral economic relations and nuclear problems 
will prevail at the meeting. As has been underlined by the U.S. 
and Ukrainian sides, it is time the dialogue was expanded and 
not reduced to problems of nuclear disarmament. Attention 
should be paid to economic cooperation and bilateral ties. 
Viktor Stelmakh emphasized that given the importance of issues 
to be discussed on 12 January by Presidents Kravchuk and 
Clinton, the Ukrainian-U.S. summit will be of great importance 
for building mutual understanding between the two states and for 
the entire world community. 

</TEXT>

