<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk, Clinton Discuss Wide Range of Issues </TI></H3>
<H4>   Clinton Concludes Visit, Departs </H4>
<F P=102> LD1201225994 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 2140 
GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1201225994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By UKRINFORM for TASS] </F>
  [Text] Kiev, 13 Jan -- A brief visit by U.S. President Bill 
Clinton to Ukraine ended late at night. A consultative meeting 
between Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk and Bill Clinton 
took place at Borispol airport. 
  They discussed a wide range of issues connected with the 
present state and prospects for the development of the 
Ukrainian-American relations. In parallel, Ukrainian-American 
talks were held in which Acting Prime Minister Yefim 
Zvyagilskiy, Foreign Minister Anatoliy Zlenko and other 
officials took part on the Ukrainian side. 
  At night, when the talks ended, the U.S. president flew to 
Moscow. 
  Earlier the presidents held a press conference at the 
airport. Answering questions from journalists Bill Clinton said, 
inter alia, that Ukraine's decision to become a nuclear-free 
state opens for it broad possibilities of getting economic aid 
from different international organizations. The fact that 
Ukraine understands the "Partnership for Peace" formula provides 
it with a possibility of cooperation with U.S. and NATO armed 
forces, something which will promote Ukraine's security, too. 
  During the meeting with journalists, the heads of two states 
told them about various aspects of the talks that had taken 
place. Kravchuk thanked Bill Clinton for his active assistance 
in the cause of developing cooperation between the two states. 
  After the press conference Kravchuk announced that he was 
prepared to give a television interview to national television 
and CNN. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

