<H3> <TI>   Spokesman on Approval Needed for Tripartite Agreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK1201140094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 12 Jan 94 
p 3 </F>

<F P=103> MK1201140094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report under the "NEGA Reports" rubric] </F>
  [Text] Regarding the meeting in Kiev between the 
presidents of the United States and Ukraine scheduled for today, 
Yuriy Sergeyev, head of the information service, stated at a 
news briefing at Ukraine's Foreign Ministry that it will be 
devoted to discussing the final text of a document on the future 
of Ukrainian nuclear weapons. This document is expected to be 
signed in Moscow on 14 January by the Presidents of the United 
States, Ukraine, and Russia. According to Sergeyev, there is 
still no final text of the document, and it is still unknown 
whether it is going to be an agreement, treaty, statement, 
communique, or declaration of three sides. As is known, a 
treaty and an agreement are subject to ratification by the 
Ukrainian parliament, whereas a communique, statement, or a 
declaration do not need this. 
  Yuriy Sergeyev also stated that should the text of the 
document not be agreed on in Moscow, the tripartite meeting will 
be of a consultative nature, the same as recent similar talks in 
Kiev, Moscow, and Washington. Responding to a question about 
possible condemnation by the Ukrainian Supreme Soviet of Leonid 
Kravchuk's activity, Yuriy Sergeyev said that the signed 
document should take into consi.... [apparent line drop in 
original as published] 

</TEXT>

