<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zvyahilskyy, Shahal Discuss Cooperation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301104294 Kiev UNIAN in Ukrainian 1539 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301104294 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kiev -- On 11 January, acting Prime Minister Yukhym 
Zvyahilskyy gave a private dinner, where he discussed numerous 
issues concerning bilateral economic cooperation with members of 
the Israeli delegation. In an interview with a UNIAN 
correspondent, Moshe Shahal, minister of police, energy, and 
infrastructure, noted: "With regard to our state's participation 
in the structure of the Black Sea Economic Cooperation meeting 
[ChES] on the basis of an associate member as Ivan Plyushch, 
speaker of the Ukrainian parliament, had proposed during a visit 
to Israel, Tel Aviv believes in such interaction, and considers 
that real grounds exist for fruitful regional cooperation in the 
Black Sea basin. [no closing quotation mark as received] 
  Israel took part in the last ChES that was held in December 
in Sofia. As competent persons from Ukraine's Foreign Economic 
Relations Ministry added, the foundation of the ChES 
international community is still in an organizational stage of 
being founded, and participation in it by new members, apart 
from the 11 real members (Ukraine, Russia, Turkey, Greece, 
Bulgaria, Azerbaijan, Albania, Georgia, Armenia, Romania, 
Moldova) in particular, of Poland and Israel, is highly 
probable. At the end of January a consultative meeting is 
planned between the Ukrainian and Turkish side, possibly with 
the participation of other states that will ascertain this and 
other prospects for continuing cooperation in the region. 
  According to preliminary information from Ukraine's Foreign 
Affairs Ministry, the Ukrainian initiative on creating a coastal 
trade zone will be put on the agenda. At the moment, this is 
being discussed by the appropriate structures of the ChES member 
countries. 

</TEXT>

