<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dual Citizenship, State Language Issues Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1201162194 Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA in Russian 12 Jan 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM1201162194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Anatoliy Ladin report: "Still No Dual Citizenship in </F>
Kazakhstan, but Society Already Split in Disputes Over It"] 
  [Text] The question of the possibility of some 
Kazakhstanis' acquiring dual citizenship is still a subject of 
discussion in the republic's mass media. The newspaper ABC 
[literally ABV -- first three letters of Cyrillic alphabet], 
published by the "Karavaninform" Joint-Stock Company, reports 
that the Sokolovsk-Sarbay Production Association collective sent 
an appeal to Kazakhstan's president which, in addition to 
economic demands, raised the questions of dual citizenship, the 
recognition of Russian (a language of international 
communication) as a state language together with Kazakh, and the 
appropriate amendment of Kazakhstan's Constitution. 
  Yermukhamet Yertysbayev, secretary of the Socialist Party of 
Kazakhstan Political Executive Committee, answering questions 
asked by the sociopolitical newspaper RESPUBLIKA's [as 
transliterated] correspondent, stressed the need for state 
bilingualism in Kazakhstan. At the same time he voiced the view 
that the dual citizenship initiative should come from Russia and 
Kazakhstan at once. "If Russians living in Kazakhstan want 
this," Yermukhamet Yertysbayev believes, "Kazakhs living in 
Russia should be accorded similar rights." 
  However, there is also a totally different view of the 
matter. Some experts predict that dual citizenship could prove 
not an advantage but grounds for restricting rights. By 
becoming a Russian citizen a person, as it were, ceases to be a 
"committed" Kazakhstani. Hence the authorities' attitude to him 
may be that of a potential "foreign visitor." And problems may 
crop up at work: Should a person, say, be allowed access to 
state secrets and his career rise encouraged if he is also a 
citizen of another state? 
  During the election campaign in Kazakhstan the questions of 
state bilingualism and dual citizenship will most likely be used 
by candidate deputies to win over voters. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-56070 </DOCNO>
