<F P=100> Uzbekistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trade, Economic Accords Signed With Kazakhstan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1201154994 Moscow IZVESTIYA in Russian 12 Jan 94 First 
Edition p 2 </F>

<F P=103> PM1201154994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Shakhabutdin Zaynutdinov report: "Uzbekistan and </F>
Kazakhstan Form Single Economic Area"] 
  [Text] Tashkent -- Talks between President Nursultan 
Nazarbayev of Kazakhstan and President Islam Karimov of 
Uzbekistan have ended in Tashkent with the signing of a package 
of eight joint declarations aimed at surmounting obstacles in 
trade and economic relations and deepening and expanding 
bilateral economic cooperation. 
  In particular, a treaty on the creation of a single economic 
area (all existing barriers will now be removed) and 
intergovernmental agreements on regional banks -- a foreign 
currency bank and a clearing bank -- were signed. These and 
other documents, as the two leaders pointed out at a news 
conference, are designed to ensure the free movement of goods, 
services, capital, and manpower, as well as the implementation 
of a concerted credit-clearing, budget, tax, price, customs, and 
currency policy between the two states. 
  A special agreement records Uzbekistan's debts to 
Kazakhstan, 
amounting to more than $39 million, as a state credit. It is 
envisaged that this debt will be repaid this year by means of 
additional deliveries of natural gas, electricity, and textile 
products. Kazakhstan in turn will sell to its neighbor 2 
million tonnes of grain, 600,000 tonnes of coal, and 260,000 
tonnes of rolled metal, cast iron, ferroalloys, and refined 
copper. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

