<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shokhin Would Accept `Influential' Post in Parliament </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1201151594 Moscow KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA in Russian 12 Jan 
94 p 2 </F>

<F P=103> PM1201151594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Stas Stremidlovskiy report: "Shakhray and Shokhin, Unlike </F>
Mankind, Wave a Cheerless Farewell to the Past"] 
  [Text] Since the appearance of the famous Russian 
Federation edict on reforming the Russian Government (with a 
view to contracting it), vice premiers have undoubtedly lived 
though some worrying days: Who will remain, and who will be 
wiped out as a class? 
  KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA's correspondent put this question to 
two 
vice premiers who are also State Duma deputies -- Sergey 
Shakhray, and Aleksandr Shokhin: Will they continue to work in 
the government, or will they concentrate fully on legislation? 
  Shakhray: I have not yet received an offer to join the new 
government. 
  Shokhin: I have not yet decided. I am prepared to move into 
a leading position in parliament. This parliament is terribly 
cumbersome and complex, and the more people with experience of 
government work in it, the better. Where can I work? Anywhere, 
from speaker to committee chairman. Provided it is an 
influential committee, of course -- for instance, the committee 
for the budget, or international affairs. The latter in 
particular, because it would be undesirable to see Zhirinovskiy 
move in there.... 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

