<H3> <TI>   Leaders in Talks With Ukraine's Kuchma </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1201213394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1709 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1201213394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [by BELINFORM correspondents Larisa Lazar and Larisa </F>
Klyuchnikova] 
  [Text] Minsk January 12 TASS -- Belarusian Prime Minister 
Vyacheslav Kebich met with Leonid Kuchma, president of the 
Ukrainian Union of Industrialists and Entrepreneurs, in Minsk on 
Wednesday to discuss prospects for forging an economic union 
between the two republics. 
  Kuchma told journalists after the meeting that Kebich showed 
full understanding of the need to establish direct horizontal 
ties between Belarusian and Ukrainian manufacturers. 
  "We should think about tomorrow for ourselves, using our own 
experience," Kuchma said. He stressed the importance of 
Belarus' integrating role in the restoration of economic 
relations between former Soviet republics and supported Kebich's 
moves aimed at establishing an economic union with Russia. 
  During his meeting with Vyacheslav Kuznetsov, first deputy 
chairman of the Belarusian parliament, Kuchma said that the 
Belarusian model of integration of the monetary systems of 
Russia and Belarus is more preferable than others. He supported 
the Belarusian Government's position calling for a gradual, 
evolutionary development of the economy and rejecting shock 
therapy methods. 
  Kuznetsov and Kuchma called for strengthening both bilateral 
inter-state and direct ties between enterprises within the 
framework of the CIS economic union. 
  Kuznetsov noted that 1994 will be a year of big political 
activity for Belarus. The republic will have to determine the 
future state system, adopt a new constitution and a law on 
elections. However, no economic or political upheavals should 
be allowed to weaken friendship between the Slav nations and 
their good neighbourly and respective relations between each 
other. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

