<H3> <TI>   Differences With Russia on Monetary Merger </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1201214994 Minsk Belarusian Foreign Ministry Department of 
Information in Russian 1633 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1201214994 </F>
<F P=104>  Minsk Belarusian Foreign Ministry Department of 
Information </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] According to a BELAPAN report, received at the 
National Bank of Belarus, there remain today two fundamental 
differences between the Republic of Belarus and the Russian 
Federation on the question of the merger of the monetary, 
credit, and financial systems of the two states. Belarus is 
insisting that the payment notes of the National Bank of the 
republic during the merger of the money systems should be 
exchanged for Russian rubles at a rate of one to one. Russia 
supports a rate of three Belarusian rubles to one Russian. 
  The second issue is that Belarus is making efforts to ensure 
that Russia's domestic prices for energy sources and raw 
materials after the merger of the money systems will also apply 
to the territory of Belarus, while representatives of the 
Russian Government do not agree with this. 
  It is thought that an attempt to overcome these differences 
will be made today at the working meeting in Moscow of S. 
Shushkevich, chairman of the Supreme Soviet of the Republic of 
Belarus, with B. Yeltsin, president of the Russian Federation. 
Taking part in the talks on the Belarusian side are Vice 
Premier U. Zalamay and National Bank Board Chairman S. 
Bagdankevich. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

