<H3> <TI>   Democratic Russia Warns Yeltsin on Withdrawing Support </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK1301105094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 13 Jan 94 
p 2 </F>

<F P=103> MK1301105094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report under the "In Brief" rubric: "Moscow"] </F>
  [Text] Democratic Russia said in an open letter to Boris 
Yeltsin that according to reports it received from government 
sources, Aleksandr Zaveryukha would be among deputy prime 
ministers who are to stay in office. The movement warned the 
president that since the government was being cut primarily at 
the expense of the reform-minded wing, "a real threat looms over 
reform yet another time." "In the emerging situation we have to 
warn you that Democratic Russia, true to its principled views, 
will have to reconsider the question of its support for the 
course pursued by the president and the government," said the 
letter signed by the movement's cochairmen, Lev Ponomarev and 
Gleb Yakunin. 

