<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Aide Rules Out Interior Ministry Reshuffle </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1201120494 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1113 
GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1201120494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, 12 Jan (ITAR-TASS) -- A whole range of 
forecasts about an allegedly inevitable reform in the Interior 
Ministry system have appeared in mass media in the last few 
days. Hypothetical assumptions are also being made about 
personnel changes, says a statement released today from 
Vyacheslav Kostikov, the Russian president's press secretary. 
  However, absolutely no such conclusions can drawn from the 
decree "On the structure of federal executive bodies" signed by 
the Russian president a few days ago. The government structure 
outlined in the decree retains the Interior Ministry, only 
specifying its constitutional accountability to the Russian 
president. 
  It is only natural that the logic of reforms leads to 
changes 
both in the government and in the operation of individual 
ministries. However, as far as the Interior Ministry system is 
concerned, I have been authorized to state that the president 
and the government have no short-term plans either to reform 
Interior Ministry bodies or to make any personnel decisions, 
says the statement from the Russian president's press secretary. 

</TEXT>

