<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   More Support for Shumeyko as Federation Council Chairman </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301100194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0943 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301100194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Aleksandrova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 13 TASS - Ninety members of the 
Russian Federation Council Thursday nominated Vladimir Shumeyko 
for chairmanship of the new Russian legislature's upper chamber 
in a secret nomination procedure, thus giving him a better 
chance to be elected than in the first two rounds of voting 
Wednesday. 
  Shumeyko's name appeared on slips with nominations filed by 
every member of the chamber ahead of the actual voting, which is 
also to be by secret ballot. 
  If the same number of ballots are cast in his favour as 
there 
were nominations it will take Shumeyko over the 50-percent 
hurdle and land him safely in the chair. 
  On Wednesday, in the first round of voting this pro-Yeltsin 
candidate missed the election by a single vote by scoring 85 
votes, one short of the required 86 vote majority. But the 
second round confusingly brought his figure down to 81, just two 
votes ahead of his main rival, Siberian industrialist Petr 
Romanov. 
  The situation has changed in an unpredictable manner again. 
Today Romanov was renominated by a mere 37 people. The other 
challengers, Kirsan Ilyumzhinov, president of an ethnic Kalmik 
Republic, and Eduard Rossel, the leader of the powerful 
association of several industrial regions in the Urals, got few 
votes each and have next to no chance to be elected. 

</TEXT>

