<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Georgian, Abkhaz Delegations Continue Geneva Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301001494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2136 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301001494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Konstantin Pribytkov] </F>
  [Text] Geneva January 13 TASS -- The expectations that the 
second round of Georgian-Abkhazian talks in Geneva would be 
promptly completed have not been justified. The U.N. Secretary 
General's special envoy Eduard Brunner, who chairs over the 
meeting, had to cancel a news conference scheduled for Wednesday 
since the discussion dragged out. 
  The consultations arranged under the U.N. auspices are 
attended by a Russian delegation headed by Deputy Foreign 
Minister Boris Pastukhov. Both Brunner and Pastukhov, who are 
working in close cooperation, face considerable difficulties in 
mediating the talks. 
  TASS learnt from sources close to the participants in the 
meeting that the Georgian and Abkhazian negotiating teams had 
put forth a number of proposals and specifications concerning 
the final document, which is to reflect the key problems of the 
conflict settlement, specifically deployment of peace-keeping 
forces. The two sides also expect to draw up a special 
agreement on refugees. One of the options under consideration 
calls for creating conditions for their return originally to 
Abkhazia's one area only (most probably the Gali district). 
This issue is to be solved with the participation of experts 
from the U.N. High Commissionnair for Refugees' office. 
  Members of the negotiating teams told TASS that the 
discussion was of a constructive and businesslike character. 
However, it is not easy to surmount the differences in the two 
sides' positions, given that such critical problem as Abkhazia's 
future political status has not yet been solved. To all 
appearances, this issue is unlikely to be settled during the 
present round of talks. It is to be addressed by Georgian and 
Abkhazian experts who are expected to meet in Moscow on February 
8. 

</TEXT>

