<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Agreements Reached </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301212194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2001 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301212194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Boris Sitnikov] </F>
  [Text] United Nations January 13 TASS -- Participants in 
the Geneva talks on settlement of the Georgian-Abkhazian 
conflict have reached important agreements, U.N. secretary 
general's spokesman Joe Sills reported on Thursday at the U.N. 
headquarters. 
  The second round of talks on the all-round settlement of the 
Georgian-Abkhazian conflict has completed, the spokesman said. 
The talks, mediated by U.N. special envoy Edouard Brunner, were 
held in Geneva on January 11-13. As a result of the talks, the 
conflicting sides defined their main goal as an all-embracing 
political settlement. Furthermore, they agreed on a set of 
procedures and principles to govern the return of refugees and 
forced migrants to Abkhazia. The two sides also called upon the 
U.N. Security Council to build up the U.N. presence in the 
troubled region, according to Mr Sills. 
  The spokesman also reported that the next meeting of experts 
to discuss the all-round settlement of the Georgian-Abkhazian 
conflict was scheduled to be held in Moscow on February 8. 

</TEXT>

