<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Terms Meeting `Ambiguous' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1401112294 Kiev UNIAN in Ukrainian 1510 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1401112294 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kiev -- In an interview with a UNIAN correspondent, 
evaluating the results of the meeting between the presidents of 
the United States and Ukraine on 12 January, Volodymyr Chernyak, 
a member of the central leadership of the People's Movement of 
Ukraine [Rukh] and a doctor of economic sciences, called it very 
ambiguous. He evaluated positively the fact that Ukraine is 
losing the artificially created image of a nuclear monster and 
its international isolation, which had begun to form. He 
expressed satisfaction that Ukraine will get the opportunity for 
wide economic cooperation and will get compensation for 
dismantling its nuclear weapons. 
  Volodymyr Chernyak stressed that the future agreement 
between 
Ukraine, Russia, and the United States is not an agreement on 
nuclear disarmament in general, but solely on the disarmament of 
Ukraine. In his opinion, there is not a single norm whereby 
Russia can have weapons but Ukraine cannot. This is not a 
normal situation, all the more so when such an odious figures as 
Vladimir Zhirinovskiy can come to power in Russia. "The 
`partnership for peace' formula," said Volodymyar Chernyak, "was 
adopted by the United States under pressure from Russia so as 
not to accept countries of Central and Eastern Europe into NATO. 
There is nothing realistic in this formula. It does not 
guarantee security, not even for Ukraine." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

