<F P=100> Uzbekistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nazarbayev Notes Common Future With Uzbekistan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301235894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1901 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301235894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature] </F>
  [Text] President Nursultan Nazarbayev believes that 
Kazakhstan and Uzbekistan have great possibilities for joint 
economic development. He believes this could be achieved 
through mutually advantageous integration, which excludes the 
isolation of the two peoples who have common historical and 
cultural roots and a common future. 
  Nazarbayev made the statement finishing his stay in 
Uzbekistan. On Wednesday [12 January], the last day of his visit 
to the neighboring republic, the president saw ancient Central 
Asian towns of Khiva and Samarkand where he was accompanied by 
Uzbek President Islam Karimov. Nazarbayev saw the architectural 
sights, met representatives of regional authorities and ethnic 
Kazakhs. 
  The presidents of Kazakhstan and Uzbekistan signed in 
Tashkent Monday night a treaty on creating a single economic 
space between the two republics. The document provides the 
removal of customs barriers on the border between the two 
countries, free migration of people and movement of goods and 
services and the creation of a legal basis for the joint 
development of communications and transportation. 
  Addressing the news conference, Nazarbayev spoke about the 
need to create a similar economic union. He said that 
Kazakhstan and Uzbekistan have always favored economic 
integration and denounced self-isolation. In conditions of 
circulation of equivalent national currencies, the idea should 
become a reality, he said, and added that talking in private the 
two presidents favored equal partnership excluding any forms of 
dictate and hegemony. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-56159 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov010_o_94002" </HT>


