<H3> <TI>   Holds Press Conference, Departs </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301161994 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1200 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1301161994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By correspondents Shakhnoza Ganiyeva and Sadyr </F>
Ziyamukhamedov, including recorded interviews with Kazakhstani 
President Nursultan Nazarbayev and Uzbekistani President Islam 
Karimov; from the "Novosti" newscast] 
  [Text] Kazakhstan's President Nursultan Nazarbayev has 
completed his official visit to Uzbekistan. 
  [Ziyamukhamedov] Following the signing of bilateral 
interstate agreements between the Republic of Uzbekistan and 
Kazakhstan and the Mukus conference of the heads of Central 
Asian states on the problems of the area adjoining the Aral Sea, 
Presidents Nursultan Nazarbayev and Islam Karimov visited 
Urgench, the ancient towns of Khiva and Samarkand, where they 
visited world famous architectural monuments. This concluded 
president Nursultan Nazarbayev's official visit to Uzbekistan. 
  [Ganiyeva] What are the main political results? What new 
elements will the meeting contribute toward mutual relations 
between the two states? 
  [Nazarbayev] First, the meeting concluded six months of work 
to bring our economic integration closer. Our experts and 
governments intend the program to last until the year 2000. As 
a result of this work an agreement was signed on joint economic 
space. 
  [Karimov, in progress] ...which presupposes, above all, a 
free economy, a free movement of goods, capital, labor 
resources, manpower, services, and so forth. My view is that 
that we are now tackling problems, difficult economic problems, 
and we are thereby also settling political issues. Today we 
have made the first step toward integration. [Video shows 
presidents alighting from aircraft, sightseeing, being 
interviewed] 

</TEXT>

