<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gamsakhurdia's Last Testament Explains Suicide </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301141994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1131 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301141994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] "Aware of my position and the moral state of the 
Georgian nation, I have decided to take my life in order to 
consolidate Georgians, Abkhazians, Ajarians and other peoples 
living in Georgia," reads Zviad Gamsakhurdia's last testament. 
This document was passed to Interfax by one of his nearest 
associates, who witnessed the suicide of Georgia's first 
president. 
  "I have used all legitimate and democratic ways of regaining 
power. My people, who love me, did not do everything they could 
to support me. I think my death will unite the people of 
Georgia. Let it be a symbol of protest for all peoples aspiring 
to freedom and independence," says Gamsakhurdia's testament. 
  "Russia, you, too, are to blame for my death. You will be 
repaid a hundredfold for your unworthy deeds. You are as much 
responsible for my death as my countrymen," says Gamsakhurdia's 
testament. 

</TEXT>

