<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commandant Urges Extension of State of Emergency </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301163994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1418 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301163994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Albert Kochetkov] </F>
  [Text] Tbilisi January 13 TASS -- Tbilisi Military 
Commandant Zaza Chachua called for extending the state of 
emergency in the Georgian capital for several more months. 
  In an interview with journalists on Thursday, Chachua 
explained his call by the fact that the state of emergency 
imposed in the city on September 20, 1993 for two months and 
then prolonged for another two months has failed to restore law 
and order and combat crime in the capital. 
  Chachua stressed that at least 15,000 to 20,000 people are 
needed to keep up order in the city. At present the total 
number of Interior Ministry and regional police troops in the 
whole republic does not exceed 25,000 people. 
  Chachua said that during the state of emergency law 
enforcement bodies have confiscated 160 sub-machine guns, six 
machine guns, three grenade launchers, about 70 grenades, large 
amounts of ammunition and explosives and even one large-caliber 
gun from an armoured personnel carrier. 
  One to two out of 100 crimes reported in Tbilisi are 
committed at night when a curfew is in effect, the commandant 
said. 

</TEXT>

