<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Paralyzed' Kutaisi Appeals for Power, Gas </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1301194394 Tbilisi First Program Television Network in 
Georgian 1700 GMT 12 Jan 93 </F>

<F P=103> AU1301194394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tbilisi First Program Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Georgian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] A significant number of the inhabitants of 
Kutaisi [Georgia's second city] have remained without electric 
power and water. Naturally, inhabitants of rayons in western 
Georgia are unable to watch television. However, the situation 
has become even more complex during the last four-five months. 
Last night, for almost six hours, Kutaisi and its environs were 
transformed, as they say, into a "dead" zone. Electricity was 
cut, all work came to a halt, and telephone communications were 
severed. In short, the city and its 300,000 inhabitants are 
experiencing the most difficult conditions. There is, in 
general, no natural gas; it is not possible to supply the 
minimum amount of electric power; water is being supplied barely 
once a week. [passage omitted] 
  In spite of the situation yesterday, all municipal police 
employees are honorably fulfilling their duties. They are 
displaying particular vigilance in such extreme conditions. 
  One can state that Kutaisi's No. 1 and No. 2 bakeries have 
diesel generators on permanent standby and, as a result, the 
city is being supplied with bread. Work has not stopped at the 
bread mill. 
  In short, Kutaisi is in an extremely difficult situation. 
[passage omitted] 
  Kutaisi has submitted a request to the Cabinet of Ministers 
that it nevertheless be supplied with electric power according 
to the schedule and that the city receive natural gas once a 
week. It is impossible for such a big city to remain paralyzed 
throughout the entire winter. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

