<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commission Established To Oversee Refugee Return </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301033194 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1800 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1301033194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Novosti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] A government commission has been set up and a 
program worked out for the gradual return of refugees, says 
video correspondent Ruslan Khashig. 
  Khashig says about 20,000 Russians, Armenians, and Jews have 
returned to Abkhazia from Russia over the three months since the 
end of the war. 
  The issue of the return to Abkhazia of Greeks sent to Greece 
during the war is almost settled, and special Athens-Sukhumi 
flights are soon to be organized by a Greek firm for this 
purpose. 
  The government commission for refugees has begun 
preparations 
to return Georgian refugees to Abkhazia's Galskiy Rayon. The 
commission held a random session yesterday in the town of Gali 
and met with the inhabitants of the rayon, he said. 
  The crime situation in the area is bad, which hinders the 
return of refugees, the commission pointed out. A decision was 
made to tighten the curfew, the video reporter said. 
  Refugees are returning without waiting for the issue to be 
finalized officially. Over 500 have already returned, not by 
the bridge over the Inguri River, but by the ford, which is 
dangerous. This means they avoid the checkpoint on the Georgian 
side that, strangely, is not letting them through. The refugees 
themselves told us that it is specifically the inhabitants of 
Gali Rayon who are being hindered from returning to their homes, 
the reporter said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

