<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shokhin Claims Chernomyrdin Offered Him Government Post </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301153194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1413 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301153194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Aleksandr Shokhin told Interfax Thursday that Prime 
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin had asked him to stay in the 
government. 
  With reference to his recent meeting with the prime minister 
he said that they had talked about a specific post, but did not 
say which post had been offered to him. Earlier Shokhin had 
told journalists that if he did not retain the post of vice 
premier he would not consider his work in the government 
expedient. 
  He noted, however, that at first he would "fight" for a 
serious post in the State Duma, say the post of a committee 
chairman. "I would prefer to act in this capacity given the 
complicated situation in the State Duma," he said. 
  Shokhin refused to comment on the presidential decree on 
Cabinet reorganization, saying that he would not like to 
criticize the decree. He said, though, that if he had been 
given an opportunity to take part in drafting this document, 
"some of its provisions would have looked much better". 
  Next week, appointments to the post of vice premier and 
other 
posts are to be announced. 

</TEXT>

