<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   May Remain in Government </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301235594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2034 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301235594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Oleg Velichko] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 13 TASS -- Russian Vice-Prime 
Minister Aleksandr Shokhin said on Thursday he might remain in 
the government after an upcoming cabinet reshuffle. 
  The statement, which was made in the State Duma, the lower 
house of Russia's new parliament, on Thursday followed Russian 
President Boris Yeltsin's decision to cut the number of 
vice-prime ministers in the government from nine to four. There 
have also been numerous leaks that Shokhin and vice-premier 
Sergey Shakhray, both have been elected deputies of the State 
Duma, will not be offered posts in the new government. 
  In an interview with ITAR-TASS, Shokhin disagreed with 
statements that reductions will be made at the expense of 
reform-minded ministers. To exemplify his point, Shokhin cited 
Yeltsin's decision to appoint Anatoliy Chubays who is in charge 
of privatisation in Russia a fifth vice-prime minister. He 
added that none of the ministers of the old government has 
received such an offer yet. 
  Shokhin did not rule out the possibility that the number of 
vice-prime ministers may increase in the future. According to 
him, there are two optimum ways to form the government: first to 
determine the number of vice-prime ministers and then increase 
it or entrust federal ministers with management functions. In 
the latter case Shokhin would call for cutting the number of 
ministries by "establishing such a system under which ministers 
will have more powers in the government, while vice-prime 
ministers could substitute the premier in his absence." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

