<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin, Clinton Discussion Issues Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1301130194 Tallinn BNS in English 1905 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS1301130194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, Jan 12, BNS -- U.S. President Bill Clinton 
and Russian President Boris Yeltsin at their summit meeting in 
Moscow are going to discuss two issues that are of particular 
interest to Estonia, said Raul Malk, aide to the Estonian 
foreign minister. 
  Estonia, in particular, is interested what conclusion 
Yeltsin 
and Clinton will reach on the issue of the withdrawal of Russian 
troops from Estonia. 
  As a more general issue, it is important for Estonia what 
position the United States takes with respect to Russia's 
foreign policy. 
  Malk reminded how several countries neighboring Russia had 
painfully reacted when Russia announced the concept of so-called 
near abroad in its foreign policy. He said it was now extremely 
important whether or not the U.S. president was going to raise 
the issue at all and if the president was also to voice his 
position on the issue. 
  If Russia's foreign political course is aimed toward taking 
part in strengthening the European security and communicating 
with its neighbors according to democratic principles, the 
Moscow summit may give a new impact to the implementation of 
NATO's "Partnership for Peace" plan, Malk said. 
  "But if Russia takes the attitude that she has quite 
different rights and that she has the right to prescribe certain 
actions to others -- in their relations with NATO, for instance 
-- then things are naturally quite different," Malk said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

