<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Legislators Want Surveillance Cases Detailed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1401080994 Tallinn BNS in English 1759 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS1401080994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, Jan 13, BNS -- After the Estonian 
legislators ruled Wednesday [12 January] that phone-tapping and 
letter checks are unconstitutional, all concrete cases when 
these measures were taken must be brought to light, Deputy 
Speaker of the parliament Edgar Savisaar told BNS at a press 
conference today. 
  Savisaar said that Asso Kommer, the former chief of the 
Laanemaa Voluntary Infantry Company who is kept in detention, 
also has the right to turn to the court, since the State Court 
authorized the Defense Police to tap his phone during the 
so-called Pullapaa crisis last summer. 
  The State Court's Constitutionality Board ruled Wednesday to 
declare null and void the government decrees and the articles of 
the law on amending the police law, which regulated the 
procedure of applying special surveillance methods including 
phone tapping and letter checks. 
  Centrist MP Andra Veidemann, a member of a commission 
looking 
into the activity of the Defense Police, told BNS at the press 
conference that "the commission was familiarized with the 
mechanism of phone-tapping and given information on the number 
of times special surveillance methods were applied over the last 
six months." 
  Veidemann stated that the commission was not given the 
concrete materials on which the Defense Police based its 
applications to the State Court. 
  She also said that the parliamentary Legality Commission is 
drafting a surveillance law under which all Estonian citizens 
have the right to inquire once a year of the Defense Police and 
the Criminal Police whether their phones have been tapped and 
why. The draft law gives the police the right not to reply to 
such inquiries, she said. 

</TEXT>

