<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Denies He May Be Like Khasbulatov </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301173794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1619 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301173794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Aleksandrova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 13 TASS -- Vladimir Shumeyko who was 
elected the speaker of the Federation Council, the upper chamber 
of the Russian parliament, denied the possibility that he may 
with time become an arch rival of President Boris Yeltsin like 
it happened with former Parliament Speaker Ruslan Khasbulatov. 
  "It is hardly possible that our relations will be difficult. 
Boris Yeltsin and I share the same point of view", he said 
adding that they both stand for the strengthening of the 
presidency in Russia. 
  Khasbulatov was a staunch supporter of Yeltsin before 1991 
Soviet coup, but turned rival when Yeltsin began his market 
reforms in the country. 
  Shumeyko said his main task in the Federation Council will 
be 
to rule out "hidden intrigues, shady deals and agreements 
between factions" of the upper chamber. 
  He added that the Council of the Federation may bypass the 
State Duma, which is the main legislative chamber, in case the 
latter works "unconstructively". 
  "It is possible, in cooperation with those deputies of the 
State Duma who really want to do something, to draft lawbills in 
joint commissions and committees and adopt them right here (in 
the federation council)", Shumeyko explained, but added that 
this may be done only in "extreme situations" and in case of a 
"tough necessity". 
  Shumeyko said his election to the post of the speaker was 
the 
"triumph of commonsense". He succeeded to win the post only in 
three attempts and encountered a tough competition from his 
conservative rival Petr Romanov. 
  Shumeyko will most evidently lose his job of the first 
deputy 
prime minister and, according to a draft resolution of the 
chamber, will only be paid the same salary by the government for 
two years. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

