<H3> <TI>   Hard-Line Deputy Likely To Win </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301184894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1730 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301184894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Pavel Kuznetsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 13 TASS -- A hard-line lawmaker from 
the Agrarian Party, who was a leader of the Communist faction of 
the disbanded Russian Supreme Soviet, is most likely to become 
the speaker of the state Duma, the lower house of the Russian 
parliament. 
  Ivan Rybkin got 233 votes during a so-called "rating vote" 
on 
Thursday which is far above the majority of the Duma. Yuriy 
Vlasov, another conservative lawmaker, was second with 200 votes. 
  Rybkin's success should be attributed also to a 
representative of the communist party, Valentin Kovalev, who 
withdrew his candidacy in favour of Rybkin just before the vote. 
  The winner will be determined on Friday morning when the 
deputies would elect one of the two lawmakers. 

</TEXT>

