<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rybkin To Work for Consensus </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1401120994 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1127 
GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1401120994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS parliamentary correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 14 Jan -- The State Duma, the Federal 
Assembly's lower chamber, has elected engineer Ivan Rybkin, 47, 
to the post of its speaker. He was put forward by the Russian 
Agrarian Party. He was the leader of the Communist faction in 
the former Russian Parliament, the Supreme Soviet. 
  In an exclusive interview for an ITAR-TASS correspondent, 
Ivan Rybkin said that his position is to work in the lower 
chamber of Parliament "for consensus, cooperation, and for the 
interests of all groups and factions of deputies to be taken 
into account as much as possible." The State Duma speaker 
intends to focus particularly on defending minority rights. 
"Not infrequently in our bitter Russian history has it been the 
case that it is precisely the minority that turns out to be 
right," stressed Ivan Rybkin. 
  He said he will strive to cooperate with the president and 
the Government "within the constitutional framework," as he put 
it, and naturally maintain firm ties to the upper chamber of the 
parliament -- the Federation Council -- "on a principled and 
partner-like basis." 
  Asked whether his political sympathies would affect his 
conduct in the Duma, Ivan Rybkin said: "I think not." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-56206 </DOCNO>
