<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yavlinskiy Sees Duma's Role as Constituent Assembly </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1301153694 Moscow SOVETSKAYA ROSSIYA in Russian 13 Jan 94 
p 2 </F>

<F P=103> PM1301153694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SOVETSKAYA ROSSIYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Grigoriy Yavlinskiy, leader of the </F>
Yavlinskiy-Boldyrev-Lukin bloc, by Nadezhda Garifullina in 
Moscow; date not given; carried under the general heading "`We 
Have a Chance. Let's Fight!'"] 
  [Text] "In someone's pocket," "unfit for work" -- all 
kinds of descriptions, mainly unflattering, were being applied, 
long before the session, to the lower chamber of the new 
parliament, for which politicians and political scientists are 
not predicting a long life. What do the deputies themselves 
think? In the break I approached Grigoriy Yavlinskiy, leader of 
the "Yabloko" [Yavlinskiy-Boldyrev-Lukin] bloc. It was a 
mystery to me why Grigoriy Alekseyevich had decided to run for 
the Duma at all, and so I asked him: 
  Do you believe that parliamentarianism is possible in 
Russia, 
after the shootout at the Supreme Soviet? 
  [Yavlinskiy] First, I think it is necessary, and as for 
whether it is possible or not, let us try once again to find out 
in practice. Second, after the situation we found ourselves in 
after 3-4 October, there was simply no alternative to holding 
elections -- in any form, even with all the shortcomings, which, 
of course, we knew about. Third, the Duma will have done its 
job if it acts as a Constituent Assembly, and that is its main 
mission. It must approve two things that are fundamental for 
Russia: electoral laws and an electoral code, and it simply 
must prepare Russia for elections of a real parliament and a 
president, and for elections of local organs of power. This is 
essential. 
  [Garifullina] And how long will the Duma be able to exist? 
Is it possible that a conflict could break out between the new 
paerliament and the president? 
  [Yavlinskiy] One would wish to avoid that. But the fact is 
that the Constitution today is structured in such a way that the 
president possesses full power. Therefore the Duma apparently 
has virtually no areas where it overlaps with the president. 
But at the same time the president bears full responsibility 
for what happens in the country. The Duma was elected for a 
short term -- only two years. Well, I don't know.... I would 
not wish to make pessimistic predictions. But if you think that 
after it is dissolved the next Duma will be better, I have grave 
doubts of that. 
  The majority of my voters did not participate in the vote, 
because the attitude to the elections themselves was negative, 
people did not have confidence in how they were organized, how 
they were called, how they were conducted, who supervised them. 
That was inevitable: When an authoritarian regime holds 
elections, it holds them in order to strengthen itself. But 
this is our road and we must follow it. We have a chance. 
Let's fight! 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-56210 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov010_c_94017" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-010 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Details of State Duma Factions Given </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301153894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1413 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301153894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] By 13:00 on January 13, seven factions had been 
registered in the State Duma. One more faction - the Communist 
Party of the Russian Federation - appealed for registration, 
head of the State Duma's temporary secretariat Sergey Stankevich 
told the State Duma. 
  He also announced that one group of deputies - the New 
Regional Policy - had been registered (see the 12:30 news 
bulletin for details). 
  Stankevich presented information about the number of 
deputies 
in the registered associations (as of 13:00). 
  Russia's Choice, led by Vice Premier Yegor Gaydar - 75 
members; 
  The New Regional Policy, led by Vladimir Medvedyev - 65 
members; 
  The faction of the Liberal-Democratic Party, led by Vladimir 
Zhirinovskiy - 63 members; 
  The Agrarian Party faction (Mikhail Lapshin) - 55 members; 
  The Communist Party faction (Gennadiy Zyuganov) - 45 
members; 
  The Party of Russian Unity and Concord (Sergey Shakhray) - 
30 
members; 
  The faction of the Yavlinsky-Boldyrev-Lukin bloc (Grigoriy 
Yavlinskiy) - 25 members; 
  Women of Russia (Yekaterina Lakhova) - 23 members; 
  The faction of the Democratic Party of Russia (Nikolay 
Travkin) - 15 members. 
  Stankevich noted, however, that those figures were not final 
because deputies continued to apply for membership in the State 
Duma factions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

