<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Highlights of 1st State Duma Deputies Group </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301160994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1413 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301160994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Zamyatina] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 13 TASS -- The first deputies' group 
has been registered in the State Duma along with the nine party 
factions, under the name, "New Regional Politics". Chairman of 
the Oil-Workers Union Vladimir Medvedev is the leader of this 
group in the lower chamber of the newly elected Russian 
parliament. 
  Yuriy Voevoda told ITAR-TASS that the group has 65 members. 
It consists mainly of representatives of industrial circles 
with Medvedev at their head. Former Secretary of the Central 
Committee of the Soviet Communist Party Aleksandr Dzasokhov, who 
gathered around himself regional representatives, including 
those from the North Caucasus, added another twenty or so 
members to the group. 
  So far the group's members are united by the slogan, "Strong 
regions - a strong federation". But many of the deputies 
interpret this phrase, first voiced by Boris Yeltsin, in 
different ways. Some of the deputies think it is their duty to 
force the reduction of the percentage of overall income 
transferred by local governments to the center down to thirty 
per cent. 
  Voevoda and his allies think that the regions should use 
their own resources to solve their internal problems, perhaps by 
attracting funds from the international community. The 
districts who have free economic zones on their territory, like 
the Kaliningrad region and in the Far East, see this option as 
being a possibility for their own areas. 
  It is obvious that State Duma deputies are going to lobby 
the 
parliament for the interests of their home districts. Voevoda, 
for example, intends to use the support of his deputies' group 
to enact a law declaring a special status for the Kaliningrad 
region, so that the region can become "an object of 
international law for the resolution of all its problems without 
asking the centre for permission". The Kaliningrad region's 
difficult location, which is territorially cut off from Russia 
proper, makes it necessary for it to develop its own independent 
policies concerning the surrounding states in order to establish 
optimal border, transport, and energy systems, Voevoda asserted. 
  He said that part of the deputies' group intend to have 
another look at specific articles of the federal treaty and will 
push to make that document an integral part of the Russian 
Constitution. 
  The "New Regional Politics" group can be classified as 
centrist. Therefore, the "regionalists'" position will have the 
power to seriously influence the adoption of decisions in the 
parliament, depending on whether the group aligns itself with 
the "left" or the "right" blocs on any given question. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

