<F P=100> WESTERN REGION </F>
<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shushkevich To Discuss Economic Cooperation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301232894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1215 
GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1301232894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Minsk, 13 Jan (TASS-BELINFORM)--Belarus intends to 
build economic relations with the United States primarily 
through the implementation of specific programs promoting trade 
and investments, Stanislav Shushkevich, chairman of the Republic 
of Belarus' Supreme Soviet, said today on the eve of U.S. 
President Bill Clinton's visit to Minsk. 
  According to the Belorusian leader, although affected by the 
Chernobyl catastrophe and floods more than others through no 
fault of its own, the republic did not attach prime importance 
to humanitarian aid in the past, either. In the opinion of the 
head of Belorusian parliament, the state's foreign economic 
policy should aim not at "patching up holes but at a search for 
ways of proper economic cooperation with foreign partners and, 
first of all, with the United States", something to be discussed 
during Bill Clinton's visit. 
  Shushkevich noted that the Belorusian side had drawn up 
concrete proposals to be discussed with the American side. It 
is not ruled out that conversation will touch upon the United 
States' assistance in implementing measures linked to the 
withdrawal of nuclear weapons from Belarus. 
  As regards the Belorusian side's other proposals, he 
believed 
that it was too early to announce them prior to the meeting with 
Bill Clinton. 
  Answering a question about why the program for the U.S. 
delegation's stay in the Republic of Belarus included separate 
meetings with the head of parliament and the head of executive 
authority, Shushkevich noted that this was in no way connected 
with different positions upheld by legislative and executive 
authorities. "Since the U.S. President is the head of supreme 
executive authority and has great powers in legislative 
activity, both sides have agreed to hold two separate meetings, 
with the chairman of the Supreme Soviet and the chairman of the 
Council of Ministers," Shushkevich said. 

</TEXT>

