<H3> <TI>   Latvian Talks' Delegation Leader Comments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301131694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1106 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301131694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Galina Kuchina] </F>
  [Text] Riga January 13 TASS -- "The whole package of 
agreements dealing with the troop withdrawal from Latvia may be 
signed as early as in February," ambassador at large Sergey 
Zotov, head of the Russian delegation, told ITAR-TASS. 
  After the end of the talks that lasted two days, Zotov had a 
meeting with Latvian Prime minister Valdis Birkavas. Both sides 
pointed to perceptible progress, achieved on the key issues. A 
complex agreement on the legal status of a Russian anti-missile 
radar station in Skrunde has almost been completed. An 
agreement may be reached even on the most controversial issue -- 
the time- limit of the functioning of the radar station. 
  The Latvian prime minister again offered apologies to the 
Russian side about the incident [as received], that took place 
in Latvia, and said the government was taking measures for 
preventing in the future the actions that could have a negative 
impact on bilateral relations. 

</TEXT>

