<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talks `Productive' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301142394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1131 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301142394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sergey Zotov, the Russian chief negotiator at talks 
with Latvia, thinks that the package of agreements on withdrawal 
of Russian troops from that country may be drafted in February. 
  He told Interfax that the meeting of chief negotiators that 
ended in Riga Wednesday was "productive." 
  That meeting was delayed until Latvia apologized for the 
incident of January 10 when Latvian territorial troops blocked 
numerous buildings belonging to the Russian Army in the Latvian 
capital and held two Russian generals handcuffed for hours 
before releasing them by order of Latvian President Guntis 
Ulmanis. 
  In the words of Zotov, the provocation against the Russian 
troops on the day when the Russian delegation stayed in Riga 
unexpectedly facilitated the Russo-Latvian talks. 
  He said that a broad understanding was reached on the legal 
status of the Russian radar station in the village of Skrunda 
and an agreement on the deadline for its closure seems possible. 
  The Russian delegation which had insisted on keeping the 
station under Russian control for six years agreed to reduce 
that time to five years. The Latvian authorities had wanted the 
station dismantled in three years. 
  Zotov added that Latvian Prime Minister Birkavs had also 
noted the success of the talks when the two men met on January 
12. Birkavs said then that the Latvian government would do its 
best to prevent activities that could have a negative impact on 
the bilateral relations and obstruct the talks between Russia 
and Latvia. 
  The two men agreed that efforts must be redoubled to draft 
the agreements and create a legal basis for normal development 
of the Russo-Latvian relations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

