<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliament Approves Local Election Law </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1401080194 Tallinn BNS in English 1759 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS1401080194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Riga, Jan 13, BNS -- Latvian local governments will 
be elected in a direct and proportional ballot for an office of 
three years, under the law on local elections, passed Thursday 
by the Latvian Saeima (parliament). 
  Lawmakers fixed May 22 the date for the elections. Electors 
are all Latvian citizens, which have full 18 years of age on the 
election day. 
  Persons serving their term or waiting for a sentence in 
places of detention are barred from the elections, under the 
law. Persons recognized as irresponsible also should not 
participate in the local elections. 
  A deputy candidate is a Latvian citizen, over 21 year of 
age, 
a permanent resident of the electoral district for at least 
twelve months. Knowledge of the Latvian language is another 
prerequisite for being elected a local deputy. 
  Persons serving their term or waiting for a sentence in 
places of imprisonment, as well as irresponsible persons, are 
barred from being elected to local governments. The ban also 
refers to persons convicted for grave crimes and persons having 
collaborated with foreign reconnaissance services. 
  The Saeima voted down a proposal by the Democratic Party and 
the National Independence Movement to bar double citizens from 
running for the local governments. 
  Lawmakers also rejected a proposal by Homeland and Freedom's 
Janis Straume to bar former functionaries of the Communist Party 
and Komsomol from the elections. 
  There was no separate vote on the participation of 
non-citizens in the elections. This issue may be approached only 
after the adoption of the law on citizenship, the deputies said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

