<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Constitutional Group Rejects Kravchuk Proposal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301204994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1845 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301204994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Constitutional Commission ended its session in 
Kiev late on Wednesday [12 January] by rejecting President 
Kravchuk's proposal for a new constitution and a law on power 
sharing to be put for a nationwide referendum. 
  The session involved regional legislators and administrators 
and leaders of political parties and movements. 
  Instead, the Commission approved a proposal by Parliamentary 
Chairman Ivan Plyushch saying that only constitutional clauses 
on power sharing in the center and regions must be brought for 
discussion by parliament due to open on January 20 before these 
are approved in a referendum. 
  Plyushch will lead a working group to draft main 
constitutional provisions to be adopted by a new parliament. 
  The Supreme Soviet did not authorize the Commission to bring 
a new constitution under a referendum, head of the law 
commission Alexander Kotsyuba said. He said the paper must be 
adopted by the next session of parliament, but any controversial 
points be put for a referendum. 

</TEXT>

