<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk on Preferred Version of New Constitution </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK1301131094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 13 Jan 94 
p 3 </F>

<F P=103> MK1301131094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Vladimir Skachko report: "New Constitution Can Be Passed </F>
in Referendum, After Which Local Authorities Will Be 
Transformed"] 
  [Text] A full-scale session of the Constitutional 
Commission attended by the chairmen of oblast soviets, 
representatives of Ukraine's president in oblasts, and leaders 
of political parties, trade unions, and other public 
associations was held yesterday on the premises of the Supreme 
Soviet of Ukraine and chaired by Ukraine President Leonid 
Kravchuk and Parliament Speaker Ivan Plyushch. President Leonid 
Kravchuk, a cochairman of the Constitutional Commission, said in 
his introductory remarks that the conference is supposed to 
explore avenues for a constitutional process in Ukraine because 
it "is a state recognized by the world community, hence it 
should not stand aloof from civilized constitutional norms." 
According to Leonid Kravchuk, the objective of passing a new 
constitution should be such a separation of the functions of 
powers where "each power branch should be authoritative, not 
authoritarian." Leonid Kravchuk outlined his own pattern of 
such a separation of the functions of powers: The president is 
taken out of the system of executive branch to become head of 
state; the parliament remains the sole legislative organ 
carrying out the legislative, founding, and control functions; 
whereas the prime minister, who becomes head of the executive 
branch and forms the government, shall be accountable to 
parliament in all respects. 
  In Leonid Kravchuk's opinion, one of the acceptable ways to 
pass a new constitution is a nationwide referendum which can be 
held simultaneously with the parliamentary elections on 27 March 
-- but to enable this, the mechanics for the final discussion 
and approval of the constitution's text and its passage via 
parliament should be determined. Leonid Kravchuk named as 
another condition for putting the constitution to a referendum 
the elimination of all political inconsistencies in the text of 
the fundamental law that could aggravate the standoff in society. 
  Leonid Kravchuk specified as other options for setting in 
motion a constitutional process in Ukraine the passing of a law 
on power if it proves impossible to put the constitution to a 
referendum. A draft of such a law elaborated by the president's 
team was handed out to those present. 
  Much as had been expected, those who spoke after him 
differed 
in their opinions. Some deputies spoke for passing the 
constitution, some spoke for passing the law on power. 
Gradually one more proposal jelled -- to approve the text of a 
new constitution by a constitutional assembly, an ad hoc body. 
But the final decision on this matter would most probably be 
made by Ukraine's Supreme Soviet, whose ninth session will open 
on 20 January. Advocates of soviet power, who press for a 
purely parliamentary republic, will say what they think about 
the constitution at a conference of the chairmen of oblast 
Soviets of People's Deputies in Kiev on 18 and 19 January. It is 
this conference that its organizers think should come to replace 
the All-Ukraine Congress of Soviets. Parliament Chairman Ivan 
Plyushch, another cochairman of the Constitutional Commission, 
will deliver a report at this conference. 
  According to Leonid Kravchuk, the adoption of a constitution 
in Ukraine should be followed by deciding on a system of local 
power, and a balance should be struck between the powers of the 
center and those of the regions that could please everyone. 
Many speakers warned Leonid Kravchuk and Ivan Plyushch against 
dividing powers between Kiev and oblast centers in such a way 
that would split Ukraine into 25 autonomous republics. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

