<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister Heads Meeting on Privatization </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301151394 Kiev UNIAN in Ukrainian 0953 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301151394 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kiev -- On 12 January, a conference was held by 
Acting Ukrainian Prime Minister Yukhym Zvyahilskyy, the 
Ukrainian president's regional representatives, heads of the 
relevant ministries and departments, and regional state and 
communal property funds. "In the three months that have passed 
since the Ukrainian president issued the directive on the 
privatization of unfinished construction facilities and their 
land, virtually nothing has been done," stated Yukhym 
Zvyahilskyy. Of the 9,200 unfinished construction facilities 
earmarked for privatization, in the words of State Property Fund 
Chairman Volodymyr Pryadko, only 3 have been sold after three 
months. 
  The following were named by the participants as being among 
the causes suppressing progress on this matter: The 
privatization scheme is bulky; there are no potential buyers or 
investors due to the financial and payment crisis; privatization 
is being carried out in tough conditions and there is nothing to 
gain financially. 
  The opinion of Ukrainian Construction and Architecture 
Minister Yuriy Serbin's is that, in holding up the privatization 
of unfinished construction facilities, "it has turned out that 
the culprits are state administrations that are unwilling to 
give up the facilities they think they need, though lacking 
funds to complete their construction." 
  One of the ways to speed up privatization, Yukhym 
Zvyahilskyy 
believes, is through "personal responsibility of local leaders 
regarding the implementation of presidential directives." He 
added: "Our president is very liberal. One should punish 
administratively rather than trying to talk them round." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

