<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ex-Communist Head Urges Party Legalization </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1401111794 Tallinn BNS in English 1013 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS1401111794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Vilnius, Jan 14, BNS -- Mykolas Burokevicius, 
former leader of the pro-Moscow Lithuanian Communist Party, has 
addressed the Lithuanian government with suggestions "on ways of 
getting the Republic out of a crisis." 
  The communist party has been outlawed in Lithuania and its 
former leader is listed among the 30 believed organizers and 
executors of the failed Soviet coup attempt in 1991. Some of 
them currently hide in Russia, and, according to some sources, 
in the neighboring Belarus. Lithuania has demanded several times 
to extradite the alleged state criminals, but without any 
success so far. 
  In a letter addressed to Prime Minister Adolfas Slezevicius 
and received on the eve of the third anniversary of the Jan. 13, 
1991 bloodshed, the central committee of the so called 
Lithuanian Communist Party points out "the need to restore the 
political power of the working people." Burokevicius also 
demands to legalize the communist party in Lithuania and to stop 
its legal persecution, the LIETUVOS RYTAS newspaper said. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

