<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to Clinton Visit Mixed </TI></H3>
<H4>   Duma Deputy Comments </H4>
<F P=102> LD1301124494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1149 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301124494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Ivan Novikov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 13 TASS -- Bill Clinton's visit to 
Moscow is "evidence of respect of the United States for our 
great country," Yevgeniy Ambartsumov, deputy to the State Duma, 
told ITAR-TASS. He was for a long time head of the Committee 
for International Affairs at the previous Russian Parliament. 
  "I hope the U.S. President will take advantage of the visit 
to familiarise himself even more deeply with Russian problems. 
I think the U.S. should proceed from the assumption that it is 
necessary to promote the development of Russian democracy, from 
the understanding that any sort of encirclement is not for 
Russia." In the opinion of Ambartsumov, the creation of another 
sanitary cordon around Russia should be out of the question. 
  "We are now living through a difficult period of our 
history. 
However, Russia has seen even worse times, but inevitably was 
brought back to life, like Phoenix from ashes. I hope the U.S. 
Administration thinks the same way," he said. 

</TEXT>

