<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to Clinton Visit Mixed </TI></H3>
<H4>   Deputy Foreign Minister Reacts </H4>
<F P=102> LD1301180394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1715 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301180394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Ivan Ivanov and Gennadiy </F>
Talalayev] 
  Moscow January 13 TASS -- Russian Deputy Foreign Minister 
Georgiy Mamedov said the current U.S.-Russian summit is the most 
"intense, businesslike and concrete" of all summit meetings he 
had attended. 
  The main leitmotif of the extended talks between the Russian 
and American delegations that took place in the Kremlin on 
Thursday can be phrased like this, Mamedov said -- 
"Russian-American relations have passed the period when 
bilateral relations focused on humanitarian and other assistance 
to Russia at the initial stage of reform." 
  "Now they have moved on to macroeconomic partnership, 
support 
for structural reform in Russia, transformation of relations 
between Russia, its neighbours and large countries of the world, 
and changes in the attitude of international economic agencies 
towards reform in Russia with special attention to be paid to 
its social aspects,+ Mamedov said. 
  In an interview with ITAR-TASS on Thursday, Mamedov stressed 
that U.S. President Bill Clinton has proposed a whole package of 
concrete measures to facilitate, in cooperation with other 
countries and international economic organisations, radical 
changes in approaches towards Russia to let it into the world 
markets and promote relations between Russia and former Soviet 
republics. 
  To exemplify his point, Mamedov said that the U.S. has 
persuaded international economic organisations to provide 
financial assistance to the CIS states to buy fuel and energy in 
Russia at higher prices. 
  "There is also a program of support for conversion of the 
defence industry aimed at preventing further increase of 
unemployment. The means released will be used to finance social 
programs, including job placement," he said. 
  During the discussion of the economic situation in Russia 
Clinton said that in his opinion based on analyses provided by 
American institutions Russia will be able to make a breakthrough 
in two years. This may enable it to qualify as the eighth member 
of the G-7 group. "But this is a very complicated problem. The 
American side said it would welcome such changes from the 
political point of view, adding that structural reform in Russia 
should lead to the reorganisation of the G-7 group into a G-8 
one from the economic perspective as well," Mamedov said. 
  During the talks earlier today, Clinton voiced support for 
the idea of Russia's joining the General Agreement on Tariffs 
and Trade. He also said the U.S. would abolish customs duties 
for almost 4,400 types of Russian goods, deputy minister said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

