<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   14 Jan Activities of U.S. Delegation Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   President Clinton Lays Wreath </H4>
<F P=102> LD1401072194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0713 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1401072194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Gondusov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 14 TASS--President Bill Clinton early 
on Friday morning laid a wreath at the Tomb of the Unknown 
Soldier at the Kremlin wall as a token of the American people's 
respect for their World War Two allies. 
  "Your Name is Unknown, Your Feat is Immortal" are the words 
inscribed on the red-and-black granite of the tomb. To the 
strains of sad music the president laid the wreath at the tomb 
and stood at attention as the ban played the national anthems of 
the United States and Russia. 
  The U.S. President was accompanied by Russian Minister of 
Foreign Affairs Andrey Kozyrev, Russian Ambassador to the United 
States Vladimir Lukin and members of the Russian and American 
delegations. 

</TEXT>

