<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Joint Statements Issued, Declaration Signed </TI></H3>
<H4>   Yeltsin Backs `Partnership for Peace' </H4>
<F P=102> LD1401090894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0841 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1401090894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 14 TASS -- Russia agreed to "actively 
participate" in the "Partnership for Peace" plan and the Russian 
and US Presidents agreed that Europe should no longer be divided 
and that a new security order is to be created on the continent. 
  The "Partneship for Peace" plan is an importnat element of 
the new security order and Russia is going to actively 
participate in it, according to the Moscow Declaration signed by 
Boris Yeltsin and Bill Clinton on Friday. 
  "The Partnership for Peace... is an importnat element of 
emerging new European security architecture. President Yeltsin 
informed President Clinton of Russia's intention to participate 
actively in the Partnership for Peace and to conclude 
substantive agreements opening way [as received] for broad and 
intensive cooperation between NATO and Russia as a partner", the 
declaration said. 
  "Proceeding from the conviction that new divisions of Europe 
must be avoided, the Presidents... agreed upon the need to 
create a new European security order that is inclusive, 
non-discriminatory and focused on practical political and 
security cooperation", according to the document. 
  Clinton welcomed the prospect of Russia's active 
participation in the "Partnership for Peace", the declaration 
said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

