<H3> <TI>   Joint Statements Issued, Declaration Signed </TI></H3>
<H4>   Other Documents Signed </H4>
<F P=102> LD1401142194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1407 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1401142194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Ivan Ivanov and Gennadiy </F>
Talalayev] 
  [Text] Moscow January 14 TASS -- Twelve bilateral documents 
have been adopted during the Russian-American summit according 
to the latest official information received by ITAR-TASS. 
  This morning Russian President Boris Yeltsin and U.S. 
President Bill Clinton signed in the Kremlin the Moscow 
declaration confirming the fundamental importance of 
Russian-American cooperation for global stability. 
  Joint statements on human rights and on non-proliferation of 
weapons of mass destruction and the means of their delivery were 
adopted on behalf of the Presidents of the two countries. 
  Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev and U.S. Secretary 
of 
State Warren Christopher signed intergovernment agreements on 
air links, on cooperation in health services and biomedical 
research, on cooperation in the study of radiation hazards for 
human health and the environment, as well as the memorandum of 
intent on cooperation in export controls. 
  Joint statements on export controls and on the Middle East 
were adopted on behalf of the heads of the foreign policy 
departments of Russia and the United States. 
  A package of documents on the implementation of the second 
stage of the 1989 Wyoming memorandum and the contract on the 
sale of low-grade uranium extracted from enriched uranium were 
also signed in the framework of the summit. The joint statement 
of intent was also announced to implement the Russo-American 
"partnership" programme of exchange of entrepreneurs and 
specialists ("Business for Russia"). 

</TEXT>

