<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Makes Statement Upon Arrival </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301230294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1959 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301230294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] President Leonid Kravchuk of Ukraine declared upon 
his arrival in Moscow that the documents on nuclear disarmament 
to be signed by the leaders of the U.S., Russia, and Ukraine on 
Friday were the fruit of natural compromises. 
  Ukraine gets compensation for battlefield nuclear weapons. 
"We have also secured smooth economic relations, confirmed 
territorial integrity, respect for each other, and partnership," 
Kravchuk said. "That, he added, can hardly be called a 
compromise because such relations are taken for granted as 
absolutely normal ties, only we have been getting used to them 
with difficulty so far." 
  Talking to an Interfax correspondent, Kravchuk voiced 
confidence that parliament would ratify the accords as they 
offer a good solution to this very complex world problem. 
  "The people and parliament of Ukraine will see that their 
republic is treated with respect as a country rather than a 
second rate nation and that all issues are being settled fairly." 
  The president voiced readiness to risk his political career. 
"The career of a politician cannot compare with the global 
problem we are solving. I do not put my career above this 
global issue. I will do all I can so that Ukraine does not 
stand in the way of nuclear disarmament," Kravchuk stressed. 
  He reported that Russia and Ukraine were working out a 
friendship treaty that would rest on a new basis and awareness 
of responsibility to people and history. "We will remove the 
acute issues dividing us. We will resolve the nuclear problem 
tomorrow. And then we will settle the problem of the Black Sea 
Fleet," the Ukrainian president said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

