<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lobov on Nuclear-Free Neighbor State </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1401090994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0820 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1401090994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Ivan Ivanov and Gennadiy </F>
Talalayev] 
  [Text] Moscow January 14 TASS -- The agreements concluded 
between Presidents Boris Yeltsin, Bill Clinton and Leonid 
Kravchuk on the withdrawal of nuclear warheads from Ukrainian 
territory "will tell most positively on the Russian national 
security", because Russia thereby gets a nuclear-free neighbour 
state, ITAR-TASS was told today at the Kremlin by Secretary of 
the Russian Security Council Oleg Lobov. 
  He confirmed that Russia and the United States "will give 
Ukraine the broadest possible guarantees of security as a 
nuclear-free power". 
  "The main thing is that Ukraine has confirmed its 
nuclear-free power status and has agreed to hand over its 
nuclear warheads to the Russian side," Lobov stressed, noting, 
that "Russia will have to pay compensation, of course, by 
delivering nuclear fuel to Ukrainian atomic power plants". 
  The secretary of the Russian Security Council described 
Ukraine's decision concerning nuclear weapons as "a very good 
step towards normalising relations with Russia", which must be 
developed on the basis of "partnership, trust, joint 
participation in the organisation of a European security system". 
  Asked whether Ukraine could again sharply raise the question 
of the Black Sea Navy after having relinquished its nuclear 
weapons to Russia, Lobov said: "I think the two problems should 
not be linked. The existing Black Sea Navy problem must be 
examined separately. I think that there should be no 
'bargaining' over it". 
  Lobov admitted that Russia would have to make some financial 
spendings linked with the transfer of Ukrainian warheads to its 
territory and with deliveries of low-enriched uranium to 
Ukraine. Nevertheless, he noted that "Russia is getting in 
return highly enriched weapon Uranium and, in addition, it will 
no longer have to spend money on the servicing of warhead 
storages". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

