<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Vorontsov's Naming as Envoy to U.S. `Virtually Decided' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1301171994 Moscow IZVESTIYA in Russian 14 Jan 94 First 
Edition p 3 </F>

<F P=103> PM1301171994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Konstantin Eggert report: "Name of New Russian Ambassador </F>
to United States Already Known"] 
  [Text] We have learned from informed diplomatic sources 
that the appointment of the new Russian ambassador in Washington 
has been virtually decided. The new ambassador will be 
65-year-old Yuliy Vorontsov, currently Russia's permanent 
representative at the United Nations. 
  It is expected that the presidential edict confirming him in 
the position will be signed soon after Bill Clinton's Moscow 
visit ends. The candidate for the new head of mission at the 
United Nations has not yet been decided, but people on Smolensk 
Square are convinced that it will be a career diplomat. Andrey 
Kolosovskiy, who has been mentioned as the possible number two 
contender for the embassy, will not be going to New York, since 
he will soon be getting another assignment. The 
minister-counsellor position will be taken by Vladimir 
Chkhikvishvili, deputy director of the Foreign Ministry's North 
America Department. 
  As is well known, another ambassadorial post -- London -- is 
also vacant. The conviction is being expressed in diplomatic 
circles that Britain should no longer be seen as a posting for 
honorable exile (L. Zamyatin, B. Pankin). "The posting to the 
British capital should go to a professional diplomat who is 
dynamic and self-confident," a well-informed Foreign Ministry 
source noted in this connection. "Candidates are being selected 
at the ministry." 
  But, as our contact put it, it is still very likely that 
London will go to a political appointee -- perhaps somebody 
losing a ministerial portfolio. 

</TEXT>

