<H3> <TI>   U.S., Russian Truck Builders Close to Agreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1301154194 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 13 Jan 94 
First Edition p 3 </F>

<F P=103> PM1301154194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Not Rivals, but Partners"] </F>
  [Text] Powerful superheavy trucks, with which Russians are 
more familiar from foreign movies, will shortly appear on our 
national highways. There are plans to produce them at a joint 
enteprise in Moscow set up by ZiL and the U.S. firm Packard. 
  The agreements on starting this production are largely 
ready, 
your ITAR-TASS correspondent was told by ZiL First Deputy 
General Director Valeriy Saykin. "ZiL-Packard" is the proposed 
name of the powerful truck capable of carrying over 20 tonnes of 
freight. The vehicle plus the freight and trailer weighs over 
40 tonnes altogether. 
  The first step toward this cooperation was the creation of 
the "Novotrak" joint enterprise, which sells diesel-engined ZiL 
trucks and ships some types of heavy truck from the United 
States; the second was the signing of the documents of 
association creating the "Novodizel" Joint Enterprise, which 
will manufacture more sophisticated fuel equipment for ZiL 
trucks. In the opinion of U.S. specialists, using this 
equipment will help make annual fuel savings of around $200 
million. 
  "In addition to joint production of heavy trucks," Valeriy 
Saykin concluded, "we intend to organize production of diesel 
engines in conjunction with the Caterpillar firm, first using 
foreign spare parts and subsequently switching to producing all 
the necessary components in Russia." 

</TEXT>

