<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Finance Ministry Denies Tajikistan Joining Ruble Zone </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1401184194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1453 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1401184194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russia's Finance Ministry declared that messages 
published by the mass media stating that Tajikistan is entering 
"the ruble zone" are invalid, deputy Finance Minister Andrey 
Kazmin reported to Interfax. 
  Kazmin explained that in accordance with the interstate 
agreement concluded last November, the Central Bank of Russia 
has granted a cash credit to Tajikistan totalling 120 Bn rubles 
due to the difficult political and economic situation in the 
country. "This does not mean that the republic has actually 
entered "the ruble zone," underlined Kazmin. 
  In his words, the interstate credit has been granted for 
half 
a year under the pledge of gold-currency reserves and real 
estate. The first part of this credit, 30 Bn rubles, was already 
delivered to Tajikistan in early January, 1994. 
  Kazmin reported that the issue on Tajikistan's entering "the 
ruble zone" is in the stage of development and it is premature 
to speak about unification of monetary systems. 
  Tajikistan has already declared its readiness to accept 
Russia's conditions providing for gradual entering into "the 
ruble zone of a new type" and intends to use this credit to 
exchange "old" Russian rubles for "new" ones. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

