<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seen Aimed at Promoting NATO Entry </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK1401115094 Moscow SEGODNYA in Russian 14 Jan 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> MK1401115094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SEGODNYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed INTERFAX report in the "Provocation" column: </F>
"There Was No Threat of Invasion of Latvia, Says Russian 
Federation Deputy Foreign Minister Sergey Krylov"] 
  [Text] The danger of Russian Armed Forces' invading Latvia 
following the arrest of two Russian generals has been ruled out. 
This was announced by Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Sergey 
Krylov in an interview with INTERFAX. 
  He noted that the Russian troops stationed in Latvia and put 
on high alert following the incident did not leave their base 
area and did not undertake any aggressive actions. 
  According to Sergey Krylov, this gross and unprecedented 
action was possibly aimed to provoke Russia into taking 
retaliatory measures. It is regrettable that it took place at 
the time of the Russian-Latvian talks in Riga, when progress had 
just emerged on the key aspects of the issue of Russian troop 
pullout. 
  The diplomat stressed that Russia is not intent on tough 
confrontation and is not interested in seeing the talks 
disrupted. He also noted that the incident in Riga coincided 
with the NATO summit in Brussels. "It is not ruled out that 
Russia's sharp retaliatory moves could have become a weighty 
argument for Latvia in favor of the earliest possible accession 
to the North Atlantic alliance." The deputy minister suggested 
that this was precisely the design by the action's organizers. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

