<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Japan Says Date Not Fixed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301200294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1733 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301200294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo January 13 ITAR-TASS -- One should not speak 
about any delay of the meeting of the Russian-Japanese working 
group drafting a peace treaty between the two countries, as the 
date for it has not been set, an official of the Japanese 
Foreign Ministry's Russian department told ITAR-TASS on Thursday 
[13 January]. 
  The official reminded that, during Russian President 
Yeltsin's visit to Japan last October, the two states expressed 
the wish to hold the meeting soon after the elections to the new 
Russian parliament. The mass media believed it meant that the 
date for the meeting was officially fixed for late in January. 
But in point of fact it was only an approximate date. 
  Japan's viewpoint remains unchanged. It seeks to hold this 
year's first round of the talks as soon as possible. However it 
takes into account the difficulty of Russia's domestic 
situation, the workload the Russian Government is faced with 
because of the beginning of the parliament's work, the Japanese 
Foreign Ministry's official said. The official refused to 
express some supposition when the Russian-Japanese working 
group's meeting may be held. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

