<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Japan Announces Upcoming Talks on Environment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301215594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1647 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301215594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vyacheslav Bantin] </F>
  [Text] Tokyo January 13 TASS -- The first Russo-Japanese 
consultations on the problem of the two countries' cooperation 
in the field of environmental protection are due to be held in 
Tokyo on January 26-27, an official representative of the 
Japanese Government told journalists today. 
  At the consultations both sides plan to discuss such issues 
as the prevention by joint efforts of dumping liquid nuclear 
waste in seas of the world ocean by Russia, cooperation in the 
struggle against pollution of air space, and in ecological 
protection of tracts of forests in Siberia which have essential 
influence of the planet's climate. 
  The consultations are called upon to become the first step 
towards working out concrete programs of cooperation between 
Russia and Japan in the sphere of environmental protection. 
  The forthcoming talks will be held for the first time since 
April 1991 when Japan and the former Soviet Union concluded an 
agreement on bilateral cooperation in the field of environmental 
protection. 
  One of the major results of this cooperation is that Russia 
will stop dumping nuclear waste in the Sea of Japan, according 
to an official from the ecology department of the Russia Defense 
Ministry. 
  So far Russia has had two tankers being used to store liquid 
nuclear waste which are now full to the capacity. Japan is 
reported to have offered its storage tanker to save the 
situation. 
  Japan shows a particular interest in the settlement of this 
problem because Russia allegedly dumped 900 tons of liquid 
nuclear waste in the Sea of Japan in October 1993. This aroused 
a storm of protests in Japan which is making great efforts to 
protect environment. At that time Russia explained the incident 
by the absence of storage space for nuclear waste and financial 
difficulties. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

