<H3> <TI>   Ethnic Koreans Demand 10 Million Yen Compensation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301143694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1307 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301143694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Yevgeniy Belovistkiy] </F>
  [Text] Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk January 13 TASS -- The 
administration of the Island of Sakhalin in the Russian Far East 
where some 40,000 ethnic Koreans live will not impede them from 
leaving for their historic motherland, according to Deputy 
Governor of the island Viktor Gurevich. 
  However, he told a press conference on Thursday that this 
would be a great intellectual and labour loss for Sakhalin and 
Kuril Islands. 
  The Korean disapora on Sakhalin consists mostly of those who 
were deported to the island by the Japanese before and during 
World War Two, as well as from their ancestors. 
  The press conference was devoted to the work of a trilateral 
Russian-Japanese-South Korean Commission which studied the 
problems faced by Koreans in Sakhalin. 
  The Korean diaspora demands a compensation of 10 million yen 
for each Korean, dual Russian-Korean citizenship and free 
private housing in Korea. 
  However, foreign diplomats told reporters that the demands 
would [word indistinct] hardly met. 
  10 million yen is too big a sum and dual citizenship is 
problematic in South Korea, they said. 

</TEXT>

