<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Border Troops To Guard CIS States' Borders </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1701224494 Moscow Mayak Radio Network in Russian 1930 GMT 
17 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1701224494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Mayak Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Regarding the federal border guard service at the 
Russian border troops main command. This structure was set up 
very recently in accordance with the Russian president's decree 
of 30 December 1993. It is headed by Colonel General Andrey 
Nikolayev, commander of the border troops. At a recent briefing 
he summed up the results of the work of the border troops in 
1993, and also defined future tasks. In particular, it was 
stressed that the Russian border troops will continue to defend 
the external borders of a number of CIS states. This is what 
Colonel General Andrey Nikolayev said on this subject: 
  [Begin Nikolayev recording] In 1994 the units and subunits 
of 
the border troops will continue to defend -- on a contractual 
basis, worked out on an inter-governmental and interstate level 
-- the state borders in Armenia, Georgia, Kyrgyzstan, and 
Tajikistan, and to participate in the defense of state borders 
in Turkmenia. The documents on the joint defense of the borders 
have been signed, and now they must be put into practice. 
  In this connection it is important to stress that, first, 
the 
defense of the external borders of the commonwealth states is 
being carried out, first and foremost, for us Russians, in the 
interest of Russia itself. Second, this involves the guarantee 
of its national interests in the most important geo-political 
regions, where Russia's strategic interests exist, existed, and, 
hopefully, will continue to exist. 
  I agree that cooperation in defending the border, when 
sovereign independent states cooperate in defending the border, 
is a completely new thing. There is no such precedent in 
history. But history also has seen no such thing as a state 
breaking up into 15 states in the twinkling of an eye. You 
understand, two years have gone by, and we finally realized that 
it is very important to have not only rights in the CIS, but 
probably obligations as well. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

