<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Oppose Admission </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1501090894 Vilnius Radio Vilnius International Service in 
Lithuanian 2200 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1501090894 </F>
<F P=104>  Vilnius Radio Vilnius International Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Lithuanian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Lithuanian and Estonian delegations at the 
parliamentary assembly of the Council of Europe will object to 
Russia's admission to that organization. That position was 
stated at a news conference on Friday by the heads of the 
delegations, Algis Gricius, the Lithuanian parliamentary foreign 
affairs committee's deputy chairman, and Tunne Kelam, deputy 
chairman of the Estonian state assembly. 
  The stand on the issue was coordinated in Vilnius at a 
meeting of the Baltic delegations to the Council of Europe. The 
Lithuanian and Estonian position was supported by Latvia, which 
so far has guest status at the Council of Europe. 
  The Baltic states' key argument against Russia's admission 
to 
the Council of Europe is the presence of its troops on Latvian 
and Estonian territories. Besides, the heads of the Lithuanian 
and Estonian delegations said Russia must first solve its own 
problems and stop interfering in the internal affairs of other 
states. We are waiting for Russia, as the successor to the 
rights of the Soviet Union, to make an official statement on the 
1940 occupation of the Baltic states, Algis Gricius said. 
  The parliamentary assembly of the Council of Europe is due 
to 
open in Strasbourg on 24 January. 

</TEXT>

